NT15 is one of the two symbols on the right-hand side of the start rule S → NT15 NT43.  
The only productions for NT15 are  

 NT15 → NT37 NT15  
 NT15 → NT19 NT30  

In every possible expansion of NT15, another occurrence of NT15 is always produced; there is no production that removes NT15 (no production of the form NT15 → … without NT15, and no ε-production).  
Consequently, any derivation starting from S can never eliminate the symbol NT15 and thus can never yield a string consisting solely of terminals.

Therefore the grammar cannot generate any terminal string at all, including the given one.

No

In the provided grammar, the only non-terminal that can produce the terminal ‘t48’ is NT4, via the rule  

 NT4 → 't48'  

(No other non-terminal has 't48' as a direct terminal production, and there are no unit productions of the form X → NT4.)

To obtain two consecutive 't48' symbols in the derived string we would therefore need, at some stage, a binary rule whose right-hand side contains (directly or through a chain of unit rules) two occurrences of NT4, so that each of them can yield one 't48'.  In other words, some rule should allow “… NT4 NT4 …”.

Looking through every binary production in the grammar, NT4 appears on the right-hand side only in

 NT24 → NT4 NT44   (produces ‘t48 t6’)
 NT9   → NT4 NT52   (produces ‘t48 t44’)
 NT4   → NT26 NT2   (NT4 is the head here, not on the RHS)

There is no binary production whose second symbol can eventually reduce to NT4, and there is certainly no production of the form “ … NT4 NT4 …”.  Consequently, the grammar is incapable of producing the factor 't48 t48'.

Because the target string ends with … t48 t48, it cannot be generated by the grammar.

No

The only grammar rule that can produce the terminal `t3` is  

 NT16 → 't3'.  

NT16 itself occurs nowhere on the left–hand side of any production; it appears only as the second symbol in the rule  

 NT47 → NT25 NT16. (1)

So every occurrence of `t3` must come from an occurrence of NT47 that expands according to (1).  
But the non-terminal NT25 has the single rule  

 NT25 → NT13 NT47, (2)

and NT47 has exactly one alternative rule besides (1):

 NT47 → NT27 NT6, (3) with NT6 → 't16'.

Because NT25 is defined only through (2), any derivation that reaches NT16 (and thus produces `t3`) must pass through the cycle  

NT47 ⇒ NT25 NT16  
    ⇒ NT13 NT47 NT16 …  

and this cycle can terminate only when some NT47 in it is expanded by rule (3), inevitably introducing the terminal `t16` into the generated string.

Therefore, every string generated by the grammar that contains the token `t3` must also contain at least one token `t16`.

The string we are asked to check contains the token `t3` but contains no occurrence of `t16`.  
Hence the grammar cannot generate this string.

No

The derivation of any string from the start symbol S must begin with the non-terminal NT15, because  
S → NT15 NT43.

Inside NT15 the structure is fixed:

NT15 → (NT37)∗ NT19 NT30            (1)

That is, zero or more NT37’s, followed by one NT19, followed by one NT30.

1.  If there are no NT37’s, the very first two tokens of the whole string are:
      • the single token generated by NT19, and  
      • the first token generated by NT30.

    NT19 can generate only t13 or t54.  
    NT30 can begin with a token only from NT32 or NT24 (its two possible left children).

    – NT30 → NT32 … : NT32 can start with t83 (via NT32 → 't83') or with t39/t69
      (via NT32 → NT25 …, NT25 → NT13 …, NT13 → 't39'/'t69').  
      It can never start with t11.

    – NT30 → NT24 … : every rule for NT24 begins with t87, t48, t88, t55, or t18,
      or with NT2, whose first token is necessarily t11 (via NT41 → NT45 NT5)
      but then NT24 would still have at least three tokens before NT30’s second
      component appears, making the second overall token t11 impossible.

    Hence, with zero NT37’s, the token sequence must start with
    t13 {t83, t39, t69, t87, t48, t88, t55, t18, …}, never with t13 t11 as in the
    target string.  Therefore the string cannot start with t13 t11 in this case.

2.  If one or more NT37’s precede NT19, their prefixes are limited to
      • t12 (NT37 → 't12'),  
      • t33 t11 / t33 t67 (NT37 → NT17 NT45), or  
      • t13/t54 combinations (NT37 → NT19 NT19).

    None of these possibilities can yield a first-token t13 followed by a second-token
    t11.  In particular, the only way to get t11 from NT37 is the pair t33 t11,
    whose first token is t33, not t13.

Thus the first two terminals t13 t11 in the supplied string cannot be produced by
any derivation that follows rule (1).  Since every derivation from S must follow
(1), the given string is not in the language generated by the grammar.

No
